                                                              Assignment-2
1. Setting Up GitHub
Create an Account:
Visit GitHub.
Click on "Sign up" in the upper-right corner.
Enter your email address, create a password, and choose a username.
Follow the prompts to verify your email address and complete the account setup.

2. Repository Creation
Create a New Repository:
Log in to your GitHub account.
Click on the "+" icon in the upper-right corner and select "New repository".
Name your repository "my-first-repo".
Optionally, add a description and choose "Public" visibility.
Initialize the repository with a README if you prefer.
Click "Create repository"

 Repository Cloning
Clone the Repository:

On the repository page, click the "Code" button.

Copy the URL under "Clone with HTTPS".

Open your terminal and navigate to the directory where you want to clone the repository.

Run the following command:

bash
Copy code
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/my-first-repo.git
Screenshot:
(Here you would provide a screenshot of your terminal showing the git clone command output. You can capture it using tools like Snipping Tool on Windows, Screenshot on macOS, or a similar utility.)

4. Collaborative Workflow
Invite a Collaborator:

Go to the repository settings by clicking on the "Settings" tab on your repository page.
Select "Collaborators & teams" from the sidebar.
Enter your classmateâ€™s or friend's GitHub username or email and click "Add collaborator".
Your collaborator will receive an invitation to access and contribute to your repository.
Collaborator Actions:

Your collaborator should:
Fork your repository by clicking the "Fork" button on your repository page.
Make changes to their forked repository.
Create a pull request from their fork to your original repository.
Go to the "Pull requests" tab on your repository page to review and merge the pull request.
